00:14:44.780 --> 00:14:46.080
this is really wonderful.

00:14:46.080 --> 00:14:50.460
So what I'm going to talk to you
today about is the relationship

00:14:50.460 --> 00:14:54.430
or the shaping of culture
and law together.

00:14:54.430 --> 00:15:00.170 position:56%
I was, when I started my Ph.D., and
continue to be very, very interested

00:15:00.170 --> 00:15:04.010
in how popular consciousness,
legal consciousness is shaped

00:15:04.010 --> 00:15:06.680
by popular art forms, such as film,

00:15:06.680 --> 00:15:10.250 position:56%
and the fact of that shaping I think
should be pretty obvious to people.

00:15:10.250 --> 00:15:14.050
So just colloquially we say,
for example, that too much TV

00:15:14.050 --> 00:15:16.400
or videogames is bad
for kids, for example.

00:15:16.400 --> 00:15:17.700
Why do we say that?

00:15:17.700 --> 00:15:20.520
Because in the main we
think it teaches children

00:15:20.520 --> 00:15:22.920
to like fast-food rather
than healthy snacks,

00:15:22.920 --> 00:15:27.320
to be beautiful instead of kind
and curious, to consume rather

00:15:27.320 --> 00:15:31.570 position:56%
than to make, maybe to hold
weapons rather than to build robots.

00:15:31.570 --> 00:15:34.340
Not all popular culture
is negative, obviously.

00:15:34.340 --> 00:15:36.900
It's not homogenous either.

00:15:36.900 --> 00:15:40.830
But it successfully constitutes
communities of people and thought.

00:15:40.830 --> 00:15:45.160
All forms of popular culture,
television, film, music,

00:15:45.160 --> 00:15:49.440
they all help form us and
bind us as communities insofar

00:15:49.440 --> 00:15:52.600
as we're both consumers and
admirers of that culture.

00:15:52.600 --> 00:15:57.020
And so I started wondering as a
student and as a scholar what kind

00:15:57.020 --> 00:16:00.800
of community does legal
popular culture create?

00:16:00.800 --> 00:16:04.200
If we're to look at
mainstream films or television

00:16:04.200 --> 00:16:07.760
about law what do they
tell us about how law is

00:16:07.760 --> 00:16:09.660
or should be in our society?

00:16:09.660 --> 00:16:12.310
How do they construct
our expectations

00:16:12.310 --> 00:16:14.140
about the American justice system?

00:16:14.140 --> 00:16:17.540
So I'm going to explore
this question with you

00:16:17.540 --> 00:16:19.990
and trace a history of law in film.

00:16:19.990 --> 00:16:24.640
The development, particularly,
of the trial film genre

00:16:24.640 --> 00:16:30.330
from cinema's inception in
1894 to the present day.

00:16:30.330 --> 00:16:33.850
And what I hope will be interesting
about this film history is

00:16:33.850 --> 00:16:36.390
that it's not only a
story about law films,

00:16:36.390 --> 00:16:39.520
but it's about how film is
a medium of communication

00:16:39.520 --> 00:16:44.040
and community building, shares
certain central preoccupations

00:16:44.040 --> 00:16:46.650
with law as a system of justice.

00:16:46.650 --> 00:16:51.550 position:56%
So you'll see that film is very well
suited to telling stories about law,

00:16:51.550 --> 00:16:56.340 position:56%
and I'll show how even in the
earliest stages film was preoccupied

00:16:56.340 --> 00:17:00.440
with what it means to know through
sight, with the relationship

00:17:00.440 --> 00:17:03.510
between witnessing
something and judging it.

00:17:03.510 --> 00:17:07.980 position:56%
And that these preoccupations, which
are themes throughout film and films

00:17:07.980 --> 00:17:12.100
about law, there are both questions
that are legal, as well as filmic,

00:17:12.100 --> 00:17:14.680
and they were embedded
in and shaped film

00:17:14.680 --> 00:17:16.350
and film making from the beginning.

00:17:16.350 --> 00:17:18.930
So at the end of the presentation
I'll ask some questions

00:17:18.930 --> 00:17:22.680
about the relationship between
law and film today in courtrooms

00:17:22.680 --> 00:17:26.000
and in police cars, on
Facebook, and how that history

00:17:26.000 --> 00:17:29.490
of film might shed some light on
what we should be doing with film

00:17:29.490 --> 00:17:31.350
as lawyers or judges, as members

00:17:31.350 --> 00:17:34.320
of society serving equal
justice under the law.

00:17:34.320 --> 00:17:36.260
So I'm going to start
with some definitions,

00:17:36.260 --> 00:17:38.500
that's what lawyers and
teachers tend to do.

00:17:38.500 --> 00:17:42.570
When I talk about law I'm
not talking today necessarily

00:17:42.570 --> 00:17:46.770
about statutes or cases or
constitutions, I'm talking about -

00:17:46.770 --> 00:17:49.970
I'm not talking about law on
the books, people would say -

00:17:49.970 --> 00:17:55.330
I'm talking about law's popular
incarnation, which I think one

00:17:55.330 --> 00:17:57.820
of its proudest is the trial.

00:17:57.820 --> 00:18:01.420
Trials are that ubiquitous
symbol of law and justice

00:18:01.420 --> 00:18:03.730
in our contemporary popular
culture, although they are

00:18:03.730 --> 00:18:06.710
so infrequent to be fair.

00:18:06.710 --> 00:18:11.340
And the trial is particularly
well suited to film and it's

00:18:11.340 --> 00:18:15.450
on film all the time because
as a genre it shares some

00:18:15.450 --> 00:18:19.310
of the general strategies
of film and of law

00:18:19.310 --> 00:18:24.180
that is the authority grounded in
the individual's person who claims

00:18:24.180 --> 00:18:27.620
to know and to judge the
world based on our capacity

00:18:27.620 --> 00:18:29.480
to observe and to deliberate.

00:18:29.480 --> 00:18:33.860
So the trial is based on
witness testimony and judging

00:18:33.860 --> 00:18:37.120
that testimony, for example,
and documentary evidence

00:18:37.120 --> 00:18:40.260
and film is based on
the same kind of thing.

00:18:40.260 --> 00:18:43.900
So when I talk about film I'm not
only talking about what the film

00:18:43.900 --> 00:18:48.220
or the video or the television
says, that is not only its content,

00:18:48.220 --> 00:18:52.050
but I'm talking about how
it says it, the distinct way

00:18:52.050 --> 00:18:56.850
of making meaning as primarily
visual whose significance comes

00:18:56.850 --> 00:18:59.790
from this overdetermined
and illusory conflation

00:18:59.790 --> 00:19:03.400
of images onscreen and
the event being filmed.

00:19:03.400 --> 00:19:07.830
The film constructs this community
through acts of visual display,

00:19:07.830 --> 00:19:10.230
our relationship to
what we're seeing,

00:19:10.230 --> 00:19:13.930
and it manufactures a
coherence, that is a logic,

00:19:13.930 --> 00:19:18.310
that what we see onscreen and
experience it as if it were part

00:19:18.310 --> 00:19:20.500
of our world here and now.

00:19:20.500 --> 00:19:23.270
So the story I tell will be visual.

00:19:23.270 --> 00:19:27.240
It's a kind of vision through
film and a history in pictures

00:19:27.240 --> 00:19:29.860
to create what I hope will
be a convincing trajectory

00:19:29.860 --> 00:19:32.860
of the development of
law's history in film.

00:19:32.860 --> 00:19:36.570
So let's go back to 1894 in France,

00:19:36.570 --> 00:19:39.050
which is the beginning
of film history.

00:19:39.050 --> 00:19:42.250
This is Auguste and Louis Lumiere,

00:19:42.250 --> 00:19:47.610
and they developed a portable
moving picture machine in 1894.

00:19:47.610 --> 00:19:52.850 position:56%
Just a year later in December, 1895,
in the basement of the Grand Cafe

00:19:52.850 --> 00:19:56.420
in Paris the first
movie theater opened.

00:19:56.420 --> 00:19:59.550
Showing there were four
Lumiere films, very short,

00:19:59.550 --> 00:20:01.790
they were called actuality films.

00:20:01.790 --> 00:20:04.290
Among them was L'Arrivee
d'un Train en Gare,

00:20:04.290 --> 00:20:06.120 position:56%
The Arrival of a Train in a Station.

00:20:06.120 --> 00:20:10.760
And the story goes that upon
showing of this particular film,

00:20:10.760 --> 00:20:16.500 position:56%
which is with a camera stations on
a K, and the train is growing larger

00:20:16.500 --> 00:20:20.440
and larger onscreen as it goes
closer and closer to the station,

00:20:20.440 --> 00:20:23.470
the audience screamed,
jumped up from their seats

00:20:23.470 --> 00:20:25.280
and ran from the theater.

00:20:25.280 --> 00:20:29.050
That is they were afraid that the
train was heading right for them

00:20:29.050 --> 00:20:32.640
and they were not at all accustomed
to that illusion of reality

00:20:32.640 --> 00:20:37.790 position:56%
that film motion creates, and this
1895 audience feared for their lives

00:20:37.790 --> 00:20:39.540
and they didn't see
the end of the film

00:20:39.540 --> 00:20:42.390
until they came back
and were told otherwise.

00:20:42.390 --> 00:20:46.130
So despite this aborted viewing
the French film empire was off

00:20:46.130 --> 00:20:47.430
and running.

00:20:47.430 --> 00:20:50.370
There was a pleasure in that
fear, in that form of witnessing,

00:20:50.370 --> 00:20:53.500
and the notion that film had
a particularly real feel,

00:20:53.500 --> 00:20:56.890
real and not real enabled
the audience to bear witness

00:20:56.890 --> 00:21:00.190
to something that was
projected onscreen.

00:21:00.190 --> 00:21:04.110
Now around 1902 this
genre of actualities,

00:21:04.110 --> 00:21:07.270
like pseudo documentaries,
they found narrative,

00:21:07.270 --> 00:21:08.960
and with it the reality film

00:21:08.960 --> 00:21:12.410
of the Lumiere brothers
was replaced with fantasy.

00:21:12.410 --> 00:21:16.450
The quintessential example is
of George Melies' early film,

00:21:16.450 --> 00:21:20.690 position:56%
A Trip to the Moon, and although his
films looked more like stage plays,

00:21:20.690 --> 00:21:24.800
the camera tended to be passive
while actors ran on and off stage,

00:21:24.800 --> 00:21:29.610
puppeteers moved props, the film
actually told a much more complex

00:21:29.610 --> 00:21:33.630
story and it involved the
audience in that story.

00:21:33.630 --> 00:21:39.920 position:56%
So his 1903 film, The Magic Lantern,
this is the best I'm sure here

00:21:39.920 --> 00:21:42.430
on this campus, I could
get a better than this

00:21:42.430 --> 00:21:45.550
and I may be able to ask for that.

00:21:45.550 --> 00:21:49.550
So this is The Magic Lantern and it
was his first film, it's considered

00:21:49.550 --> 00:21:52.220
to be the first film about film

00:21:52.220 --> 00:21:55.100
and it tells a history
of Western dramatic art.

00:21:55.100 --> 00:22:00.470 position:56%
So from left to right it shows first
a landscape painting, then a play,

00:22:00.470 --> 00:22:02.030
and then at the end it's the image

00:22:02.030 --> 00:22:04.800
of the newly developed
moving pictures.

00:22:04.800 --> 00:22:07.250
And by placing film
in the trajectory

00:22:07.250 --> 00:22:11.050
of Western representational
art Melies' film suggests

00:22:11.050 --> 00:22:13.560
that film art is no
more or less faithful

00:22:13.560 --> 00:22:15.670
to its subject than his painting.

00:22:15.670 --> 00:22:19.280
He also peaks the spectators'
attention, drawing the audience

00:22:19.280 --> 00:22:22.550
out of what's considered
passive experience of watching

00:22:22.550 --> 00:22:24.760
to a more active role
of contributing

00:22:24.760 --> 00:22:27.590
and to critiquing the
meaning made of film.

00:22:27.590 --> 00:22:30.090
You all of a sudden realize you're
watching a film about a film,

00:22:30.090 --> 00:22:33.340
about how film was artifice
just like everything else.

00:22:33.340 --> 00:22:38.400 position:56%
So being made to recognize that film
story is just one representational

00:22:38.400 --> 00:22:42.490
scheme among others is to
acknowledge one's own complicity

00:22:42.490 --> 00:22:45.980
in the perpetuation of the
illusion of film's omnissions.

00:22:45.980 --> 00:22:51.540 position:56%
So self-reflexivity in film, calling
attention to film's own artifice

00:22:51.540 --> 00:22:56.340 position:56%
and relying on the audience to play
along makes the audience participate

00:22:56.340 --> 00:23:00.220
in the story being told and
that was born with Melies.

00:23:00.220 --> 00:23:02.360
This self-reflexivity,
the recognition

00:23:02.360 --> 00:23:05.440
of being present beyond
the representation that is

00:23:05.440 --> 00:23:08.500
in the audience, but also
integral to the meaning

00:23:08.500 --> 00:23:13.060
of what's onscreen is one
feature of what makes law and film

00:23:13.060 --> 00:23:16.910
and their way of knowing and
judging the world so compatible.

00:23:16.910 --> 00:23:20.630
It's, for example, how audience
members might experience film

00:23:20.630 --> 00:23:26.250 position:56%
as jurors might experience trials,
isolated and apart but acutely aware

00:23:26.250 --> 00:23:29.600
of their integral role in the
justification and significance

00:23:29.600 --> 00:23:31.750
of the spectacle before them.

00:23:31.750 --> 00:23:37.290
Now Edwin Porter's Great Train
Robbery was also made in 1903,

00:23:37.290 --> 00:23:39.050
but in the United States.

00:23:39.050 --> 00:23:40.770
The Great Train Robbery
is considered one

00:23:40.770 --> 00:23:44.700
of the first pseudo documentaries,
but it's a pseudo documentary.

00:23:44.700 --> 00:23:47.860
And its subject was
how to rob a train.

00:23:47.860 --> 00:23:51.900
And I kid you not there was
anxiety and fear and popularity

00:23:51.900 --> 00:23:56.240
around this film that it was a
very effective teaching tool,

00:23:56.240 --> 00:23:59.530
telling audiences the truth
about how to do things

00:23:59.530 --> 00:24:02.240
or how life is or can be.

00:24:02.240 --> 00:24:04.310
The Great Train Robbery's
other contribution

00:24:04.310 --> 00:24:06.440
to film is its editing structure.

00:24:06.440 --> 00:24:12.530
By juxtaposing shots of otherwise
discontinuous images the filmmaker,

00:24:12.530 --> 00:24:15.720
Edwin Porter, creates logic
where there wasn't before.

00:24:15.720 --> 00:24:18.310
So think about other films
the camera stayed still

00:24:18.310 --> 00:24:23.540
and things happened in front of it
or the train, it was just a video

00:24:23.540 --> 00:24:25.920
or a film of the train
entering the station.

00:24:25.920 --> 00:24:29.350
This is about actually
stopping and starting the camera

00:24:29.350 --> 00:24:32.310
and making new shots and
piecing them together.

00:24:32.310 --> 00:24:34.850
And this phenomenon was
explained in early series

00:24:34.850 --> 00:24:40.230
of experiments conducted in 1920
by Russian filmmaker Kuleshov

00:24:40.230 --> 00:24:44.450
in which he juxtaposed various
scenes - here's an image

00:24:44.450 --> 00:24:49.600
of the Kuleshov experiment
- juxtaposing the same image

00:24:49.600 --> 00:24:54.560 position:56%
of a man holding his chin with three
different shots - a bowl of soup,

00:24:54.560 --> 00:24:57.580
a corpse, and a woman
lying in a bed.

00:24:57.580 --> 00:25:00.270
And when he experimentally
established

00:25:00.270 --> 00:25:04.900
that people would see the top
image and see the man as hungry,

00:25:04.900 --> 00:25:08.990
the middle image they'd
interpret the man as sorrowful,

00:25:08.990 --> 00:25:13.000
and the bottom image they'd
interpret him as lustful.

00:25:13.000 --> 00:25:17.310 position:56%
That is the idea that the same exact
image has different meaning based

00:25:17.310 --> 00:25:19.220
on what comes before it.

00:25:19.220 --> 00:25:22.330
Now this might make sense to all
of us, but this was not understood

00:25:22.330 --> 00:25:26.100
to be how film could make
meaning and yet it was one

00:25:26.100 --> 00:25:30.360
of the most powerful ways that
film would develop over time.

00:25:30.360 --> 00:25:33.700
Here is Alfred Hitchcock
saying the same thing.

00:25:33.700 --> 00:25:40.600
&gt;&gt; Now the third way is what
one might call pure cinematics,

00:25:40.600 --> 00:25:49.230
the assembly of film,
and how it can be changed

00:25:49.230 --> 00:25:51.530
to create a different idea.

00:25:51.530 --> 00:25:55.140
Now we have a close-up
that we show what he sees.

00:25:55.140 --> 00:26:01.640
Let's assume he saw a woman
holding a baby in her arms.

00:26:01.640 --> 00:26:08.500
Now we cut back to his reaction
to what he sees, and he smiles.

00:26:08.500 --> 00:26:10.660
Now what is he as a character?

00:26:10.660 --> 00:26:14.900
He's a kindly man,
he is sympathetic.

00:26:14.900 --> 00:26:20.190 position:56%
Now let's take the middle piece of
film away, the woman with the child,

00:26:20.190 --> 00:26:23.170
but leave his two pieces
of film as they were.

00:26:23.170 --> 00:26:29.550
Now we'll put in a piece of
film of a girl in a bikini.

00:26:30.640 --> 00:26:37.260
He looks, girl in a
bikini, he smiles.

00:26:37.260 --> 00:26:38.560
What is he now?

00:26:38.560 --> 00:26:40.290
A dirty old man.

00:26:40.290 --> 00:26:44.970
He's no longer the benign
gentleman who loves babies.

00:26:44.970 --> 00:26:50.200
That's what film can do for you.

00:26:50.200 --> 00:26:56.130
&gt;&gt; All right, so before film was
10 years old the most important

00:26:56.130 --> 00:26:58.500
technique was experimentally
established,

00:26:58.500 --> 00:27:02.070
that is the human tendency
to create relationships

00:27:02.070 --> 00:27:05.820
between otherwise totally
unrelated scenes.

00:27:05.820 --> 00:27:09.310
We, the audience, create narrative
where none existed before,

00:27:09.310 --> 00:27:12.810
we bring the story to the images.

00:27:12.810 --> 00:27:16.300
This technique of montage
was made even more famous

00:27:16.300 --> 00:27:18.660
with the filmmaker D.W Griffith.

00:27:18.660 --> 00:27:24.790 position:56%
Griffith's legacy for film and its
grammar, the close-up and deep focus

00:27:24.790 --> 00:27:27.630
and the long shot, is profound.

00:27:27.630 --> 00:27:31.080
Before his masterpieces of Birth
of a Nation and Intolerance

00:27:31.080 --> 00:27:36.480
in 1907 D.W. made one of his
first appearances on film -

00:27:36.480 --> 00:27:40.200
directors often liked putting
themselves in film in little bits

00:27:40.200 --> 00:27:42.440
and parts - and he was
in Falsely Accused.

00:27:42.440 --> 00:27:46.750
Falsely Accused is possibly
the first trial film.

00:27:46.750 --> 00:27:50.260
Here's an image from the trial
scene and I'll explain it.

00:27:50.260 --> 00:27:53.980
It contains many of the
trial film's generic markers

00:27:53.980 --> 00:27:56.050
that remain intact today.

00:27:56.050 --> 00:27:59.200
Falsely Accused opens with
a murder of an inventor

00:27:59.200 --> 00:28:03.330
and the false accusation that
his daughter committed the crime.

00:28:03.330 --> 00:28:05.000
The daughter's boyfriend dwelling

00:28:05.000 --> 00:28:08.700
on the crime scene finds
a motion picture camera

00:28:08.700 --> 00:28:12.410 position:56%
which had miraculously been running
during the commission of the murder.

00:28:12.410 --> 00:28:14.880
This is 1907, okay?

00:28:14.880 --> 00:28:17.460
He develops, so it's a
film about a film, right -

00:28:17.460 --> 00:28:21.130
he develops the film which, of
course, reveals the true murderer

00:28:21.130 --> 00:28:24.020
and rushes it to the courthouse
where he shows it to the judge

00:28:24.020 --> 00:28:26.290
and the jury to free his girl.

00:28:26.290 --> 00:28:28.540
And this is an image
of the courtroom scene

00:28:28.540 --> 00:28:32.650
where a screen is being hung
to show that piece of evidence.

00:28:32.650 --> 00:28:35.990
It's been argued that
Falsely Accused is the genesis

00:28:35.990 --> 00:28:38.060
of those trial films in
which the missing piece

00:28:38.060 --> 00:28:42.400
of evidence is magically caught on
film or a photograph, for example,

00:28:42.400 --> 00:28:44.160
which once developed
is shown to the court

00:28:44.160 --> 00:28:47.260
in this triumphant
climax to solve the crime.

00:28:47.260 --> 00:28:50.970
In addition to its self-referential
gesture making the film,

00:28:50.970 --> 00:28:54.320
the star of the film around
which the meaning of the story

00:28:54.320 --> 00:28:57.380
about law's relationship
to truth is structured,

00:28:57.380 --> 00:29:01.070
Falsely Accused also participates
in the trial film genre

00:29:01.070 --> 00:29:04.600
by featuring the film
audience as the jury.

00:29:04.600 --> 00:29:08.890
So by showing the film of the
crime in court to solve the mystery

00:29:08.890 --> 00:29:12.710
and expose the true killer
the jury within the film

00:29:12.710 --> 00:29:14.900
and the film's audience
who already knew

00:29:14.900 --> 00:29:17.580
that eventually share
the same information

00:29:17.580 --> 00:29:21.350
about who committed the murder
and can render a unanimous verdict

00:29:21.350 --> 00:29:24.600
of not guilty, releasing what would
otherwise be a substantial amount

00:29:24.600 --> 00:29:26.550
of tension in the film.

00:29:26.550 --> 00:29:28.510
So, thus, I suggest
this is the origin

00:29:28.510 --> 00:29:31.090
of the audience satisfaction
that's so much

00:29:31.090 --> 00:29:34.720
of what trial films have in them.

00:29:34.720 --> 00:29:38.560
so here in 1907 film is both
evidence and it's a story

00:29:38.560 --> 00:29:42.490
