00:49:30.040 --> 00:49:34.110
Film and law collapsed
together as joined ways

00:49:34.110 --> 00:49:37.670
of telling the most definitive
truth we can say about our world.

00:49:37.670 --> 00:49:41.240
Truth matters to law and to the
confidence in our justice system,

00:49:41.240 --> 00:49:45.460
if not also to our democracy,
but truth is not easy to see,

00:49:45.460 --> 00:49:48.570
it's not easy to see,
and it's rarely on film

00:49:48.570 --> 00:49:51.120
or television as hard
as we may look.

00:49:51.120 --> 00:49:54.870
What we see are myths and ideals
and nightmares and the truths

00:49:54.870 --> 00:49:57.050
of our lives together
is much more complex

00:49:57.050 --> 00:49:59.980
than a video image or a film story.

00:49:59.980 --> 00:50:05.300 position:56%
So after the past weeks I have to
say after Saint Paul and Baton Rouge

00:50:05.300 --> 00:50:09.300
and of Dallas it bears
repeating that policing

00:50:09.300 --> 00:50:13.120
and legal decision-making is
increasingly involving film,

00:50:13.120 --> 00:50:17.030
documentary like film, films
that compete for truth claims

00:50:17.030 --> 00:50:21.230
about police brutality, racism
and the justified use of force.

00:50:21.230 --> 00:50:25.520
Bystander videos of police
brutality don't answer the question

00:50:25.520 --> 00:50:29.590 position:56%
of whether the police were motivated
by racism and unjustified fear.

00:50:29.590 --> 00:50:32.930
We come to these films,
videos of police brutality

00:50:32.930 --> 00:50:36.160
or videotaped confessions
of guilt, for example,

00:50:36.160 --> 00:50:41.070
