00:51:04.230 --> 00:51:09.660
The early film masters would ask
whose story do they tell and how?

00:51:09.660 --> 00:51:13.590
Like most documentaries they do
not tell us what really happened.

00:51:13.590 --> 00:51:17.080
If there is an incontestable
and singular account, at all,

00:51:17.080 --> 00:51:20.560
but as visual narratives they're
particularly good at persuading us

00:51:20.560 --> 00:51:25.410
of a point of view and they can
contextualize claims to truth.

00:51:25.410 --> 00:51:28.710
They can help us tell a bigger
story, a more complex one.

00:51:28.710 --> 00:51:30.950
But, of course, the film
is not the whole truth.

00:51:30.950 --> 00:51:33.350
It does, however, participate
in culture

00:51:33.350 --> 00:51:35.600
as if it needs no explanation.

00:51:35.600 --> 00:51:37.970 position:56%
But films need a lot of explanation.

00:51:37.970 --> 00:51:41.490
Letting films speak for themselves
is leaving the world they create

00:51:41.490 --> 00:51:43.100
in other people's hands.

00:51:43.100 --> 00:51:45.620
So I cannot resist,
because I'm a Law Professor,

00:51:45.620 --> 00:51:49.280
to talk about a case in
my last five minutes.

00:51:49.280 --> 00:51:54.000
The case is Scott vs. Harris
from 2007, and at the center

00:51:54.000 --> 00:51:58.700
of this case was a video of a
car chase taken from the dash cam

00:51:58.700 --> 00:52:01.520
of a police cruiser that
was pursuing a suspect.

00:52:01.520 --> 00:52:04.010
And the video shows the
police officer racing

00:52:04.010 --> 00:52:05.950
down this dark narrow road

00:52:05.950 --> 00:52:09.820
and deliberately ramming the
suspect's car to end the chase.

00:52:09.820 --> 00:52:13.600
The suspect was paralyzed as a
result of the crash and the issue

00:52:13.600 --> 00:52:17.120
to be decided was whether or not
the police officer was justified

00:52:17.120 --> 00:52:19.780
in the use of force
to end the car crash.

00:52:19.780 --> 00:52:21.440
As you can imagine,
the focal evidence

00:52:21.440 --> 00:52:25.550
in the case was the dash cam
video, and it went all the way

00:52:25.550 --> 00:52:29.580
up to the Supreme Court and at
oral argument both Justices Breyer

00:52:29.580 --> 00:52:32.830
and Scalia vocalized this power
of film that I've been talking

00:52:32.830 --> 00:52:37.700 position:56%
about for the past 40 minutes, this
power of film and their naive belief

00:52:37.700 --> 00:52:42.640 position:56%
that film captures reality, at least
the relevant legal reality at hand.

00:52:42.640 --> 00:52:46.430
Justice Breyer noted, his
voice raised if you listen

00:52:46.430 --> 00:52:49.390
to the oral argument, he says I
see with my own eyes what happened,

00:52:49.390 --> 00:52:51.260
what am I supposed to do?

00:52:51.260 --> 00:52:54.570
And Justice Scalia exclaimed that
the video of the car chase was one

00:52:54.570 --> 00:52:58.570
of the scariest he'd seen
since The French Connection.

00:52:58.570 --> 00:53:02.280
So sure was Scalia of his and the
court majority's interpretation

00:53:02.280 --> 00:53:06.370
of the video as justifying the use
of force because the chase looked

00:53:06.370 --> 00:53:09.130
so dangerous to them
that in a footnote

00:53:09.130 --> 00:53:11.440
to the opinion Justice
Scalia invited the readers

00:53:11.440 --> 00:53:13.710
to watch the video for themselves.

00:53:13.710 --> 00:53:15.560
So he says far from
being the cautious

00:53:15.560 --> 00:53:17.850
and controlled driver
the lower court depicts,

00:53:17.850 --> 00:53:19.470
they overturned the lower court,

00:53:19.470 --> 00:53:23.370
what we see on the video more
closely resembles a Hollywood style

00:53:23.370 --> 00:53:26.870
car chase and the most frightening
sort, placing police officers

00:53:26.870 --> 00:53:30.760
and innocent bystanders alike
at great risk of serious harm.

00:53:30.760 --> 00:53:32.060
And then he says we're happy

00:53:32.060 --> 00:53:35.130
to allow the videotape
to speak for itself.

00:53:35.130 --> 00:53:39.830
I read that and just groaned.

00:53:39.830 --> 00:53:42.720
Justice Stevens was the
lone dissenter in this case,

00:53:42.720 --> 00:53:45.130
and he took the majority to task

00:53:45.130 --> 00:53:47.950
for disregarding the lower
court's factual findings based

00:53:47.950 --> 00:53:51.380
on all the evidence before it,
evidence that included much more

00:53:51.380 --> 00:53:53.000
than the film, driving conditions,

00:53:53.000 --> 00:53:56.300
common speeds on the particular
stretch of road, the experience

00:53:56.300 --> 00:53:59.610
of police officers, the
suspect's known criminal record.

00:53:59.610 --> 00:54:05.010 position:56%
And particularly he complained his
colleagues had never clearly driven,

00:54:05.010 --> 00:54:07.970
had clearly never driven on
a dark country road before.

00:54:07.970 --> 00:54:11.560
He says it's not a scary speeding
car chase, he says, it's normal.

00:54:11.560 --> 00:54:14.550
He says I can only conclude that my
colleagues were unduly frightened

00:54:14.550 --> 00:54:17.440
by two of the three images on
the tape that looked like bursts

00:54:17.440 --> 00:54:20.600
of lightning or explosion, but
were in fact merely the headlights

00:54:20.600 --> 00:54:23.080
of vehicles zooming by
in the opposite lane.

00:54:23.080 --> 00:54:25.800
Had they learned to drive when
most high-speed driving took place

00:54:25.800 --> 00:54:28.370
on two lane roads rather
than on superhighways,

00:54:28.370 --> 00:54:31.180
when split second judgment is about
the risk of passing a slowpoke

00:54:31.180 --> 00:54:33.440
in the face of oncoming
traffic were routine,

00:54:33.440 --> 00:54:37.550
they might well have reacted to
the videotape more dispassionately.

00:54:37.550 --> 00:54:40.470
So, in other words, he says don't
just fall victim to the effects

00:54:40.470 --> 00:54:44.660 position:56%
on screen, consider the evidence
that can contextualize what you see.

00:54:44.660 --> 00:54:47.900
He does what many film
and cultural critics do,

00:54:47.900 --> 00:54:52.110 position:56%
he asks how the film's portrayal of
the event is being shaped and coaxed

00:54:52.110 --> 00:54:55.810
by particular experiences and
points of view, a bird's eye view

00:54:55.810 --> 00:54:59.000
on the dashboard, for
example, rather than from above

00:54:59.000 --> 00:55:01.860
or alongside the car, which would
have given you a very different

00:55:01.860 --> 00:55:06.150
sense of how fast the car was going
and how dangerous things were.

00:55:06.150 --> 00:55:11.430
A long shot rather than a close-up
would have made all the difference

00:55:11.430 --> 00:55:12.730
in this video.

00:55:12.730 --> 00:55:16.230
He manifests a healthy
skepticism towards film that claims

00:55:16.230 --> 00:55:19.380
to depict the truth
or speaks for itself.

00:55:19.380 --> 00:55:22.760
He does not disregard the film,
that's an important point,

00:55:22.760 --> 00:55:26.120
he just understands its power and
its relevance and he simply asks

00:55:26.120 --> 00:55:30.010 position:56%
